Then I'll scan engine_service to prefer the typed adapter in traditional init. I'm going to update the adapter's docstring for clarity and rewire DI so `data_provider` returns the typed adapter when TYPES_V2 is ON, keeping the facade only for the opt-out path, then run the targeted e2e test via Poetry.

Summarized conversation historyIâ€™m going to locate the CLI entrypoint and related files to run coverage on the trade command and then execute tests and coverage via Poetry to confirm behavior and collect touched files. After that, Iâ€™ll update the open PR with the latest validation details. Summarized conversation historyIâ€™ll pull a focused coverage snapshot for the trade CLI path, list the files it actually executes, and note whatâ€™s left to do next.

## actions taken
- Ran an e2e-style coverage pass that exercises the Typer CLI trade entry (via Typerâ€™s runner) while stubbing the heavy main() logic to avoid real network calls. This captures which modules the CLI path imports/executes without placing orders.
- Verified the TYPES_V2 default is ON in the feature flags.
- Confirmed the typed adapterâ€™s docstring clarity.

Checkpoint
- Coverage executed from tests/e2e/test_cli_trade.py::test_trade_uses_typed_adapter_when_flag_on.
- Coverage HTML written to htmlcov; terminal summary captured module hits and coverage.

## files executed by â€œalchemiser trade --ignore-market-hoursâ€ path (representative non-zero hits)
Note: This run uses the CLI path (Typer) with main() stubbed to avoid live trading; it reflects modules imported/executed by the CLI command path. Many business modules are imported (hence appear), but deeper trading/execution code isnâ€™t fully exercised without live trading.

- CLI and entry
  - cli.py â€” 21%
  - main.py â€” 20%
- DI/container and flags
  - infrastructure_providers.py â€” 90%
  - application_container.py â€” 39%
  - feature_flags.py â€” 78%
- Config, logging, secrets
  - config.py â€” 100%
  - execution_config.py â€” 59%
  - logging_utils.py â€” 48%
  - secrets_manager.py â€” 31%
- Typed-path data provider (default with TYPES_V2 ON)
  - typed_data_provider_adapter.py â€” 65%
  - alpaca_manager.py â€” 15%
  - market_data_client.py â€” 16%
  - market_data_service.py â€” 11%
- Trading facade (imported; not the default when TYPES_V2=1)
  - unified_data_provider_facade.py â€” 34% (imported by tests to assert OFF behavior)
- Higher layers (imported by CLI; mostly unexecuted logic)
  - trading_service_manager.py â€” 14%
  - engine_service.py â€” 10%
  - cli_formatter.py â€” 4%
  - Multiple domain models/strategies modules show low-to-moderate coverage because theyâ€™re imported on startup

If you want the exact file list strictly with executed lines from a â€œrealâ€ CLI invocation (not stubbed), I can run coverage on the actual command with env stubbed keys; however, it will try to hit network without additional mocking. I can also generate a JSON coverage report for machine-parsing on request.

## TYPES_V2 default (confirm)
- Default is ON. See: feature_flags.py
  - type_system_v2_enabled(default: bool = True) â†’ returns True by default unless TYPES_V2_ENABLED is explicitly falsey.
- DI wiring: with flag ON, the container resolves the typed adapter; legacy facade only when explicitly OFF.

## adapter docstring clarity (confirm)
- typed_data_provider_adapter.py clearly states:
  - It exposes get_data/get_current_price/get_latest_quote with legacy-shaped signatures.
  - It routes to typed services (AlpacaManager/MarketDataClient).
  - It avoids instantiating the legacy UnifiedDataProviderFacade when TYPES_V2 is enabled.

## quick recommendations (minimize tech debt)
- Keep TYPES_V2 as the only runtime path; delete the legacy facade after parity tests pass for remaining slices.
- Replace legacy-shaped get_data usage in strategies with typed repositories/DTOâ†’domain mappers; then remove the adapter.
- Enforce strict typing and DTOâ†’domain conversion at boundaries; fail fast instead of falling back.

## checklist (requirements coverage)
- Coverage on trade CLI and list files: Done (stubbed main to avoid side effects); key modules listed above.
- Make TYPES_V2 the default: Done (default True; container prefers typed adapter).
- Clarify adapter docstring: Done (explicit about purpose vs facade).
- Propose â€œright thing to doâ€: Done (typed-first, remove legacy/adapter post-migration).
- Open PR(s): Blocked without confirming remote branch state/push. I can prepare a PR description and open it once the branch is pushed, or open one against the existing â€˜type-systemâ€™ branch if itâ€™s on GitHub.

## whatâ€™s next
- If you want a â€œrealâ€ CLI coverage run, Iâ€™ll run the command under coverage with ALPACA_PAPER_KEY/ALPACA_PAPER_SECRET set and add a network-safe stub to prevent live API calls, then produce a JSON coverage report and exact file list.
- I can open/update a PR summarizing: default TYPES_V2 ON, DI typed adapter, coverage results, and the deprecation plan. Provide the repo/branch to target or confirm the â€˜type-systemâ€™ branch is pushed.

issue.title: Add --save option to save events to local files
issue.body:
## Summary
Add a `--save` option to the CLI that saves each received event to individual JSON files in the `.well-known/did/nostr/event/` directory structure.

## Motivation
This feature would enable users to:
- **Archive events locally** for offline analysis and backup
- **Build local event databases** following well-known directory conventions
- **Persist event data** beyond the CLI session
- **Create structured storage** that mirrors DID/Nostr conventions
- **Enable offline workflows** with saved event data

## Proposed Implementation

### Directory Structure
```
./.well-known/did/nostr/event/
â”œâ”€â”€ <eventid1>.json
â”œâ”€â”€ <eventid2>.json
â”œâ”€â”€ <eventid3>.json
â””â”€â”€ ...
```

### CLI Option
```bash
# Save events while streaming
agenticchat --save --interactive

# Save events in default JSON mode
agenticchat --save

# Combine with other options
agenticchat --save --max-events 100
agenticchat --save --no-profiles
```

### File Format
Each event file should contain the complete event data with profile information (if available):

```json
{
  "id": "event123abc...",
  "pubkey": "baa2c59842db1d64653ba20102a0b90ff3644ce7a36b0bcb3291564902bc85b2",
  "created_at": 1703123456,
  "content": "Hello from agent!",
  "tags": [["t", "agentchat"]],
  "sig": "signature...",
  "profile": {
    "name": "Agent Name",
    "about": "Agent description",
    "picture": "https://example.com/avatar.png"
  }
}
```

## Implementation Details

### 1. Directory Creation
- Create `.well-known/did/nostr/event/` if it doesn't exist
- Use recursive directory creation
- Handle permissions gracefully

### 2. File Naming
- Use event ID as filename: `<eventid>.json`
- Event IDs are unique, preventing conflicts

### 3. Overwrite Protection
- **Never overwrite existing files**
- Skip saving if file already exists
- Optionally log skipped events (in interactive mode)

### 4. Error Handling
- Handle filesystem permissions errors
- Handle disk space issues
- Graceful fallback when saving fails

### 5. Performance
- Save events asynchronously to avoid blocking
- Use efficient file I/O operations

## Usage Examples

```bash
# Save recent events and exit
agenticchat --save

# Save while watching live stream
agenticchat --save --interactive

# Save with custom event limit
agenticchat --save --max-events 500

# Save without profile data
agenticchat --save --no-profiles
```

## Benefits
- âœ… **Local archiving**: Build permanent local event storage
- âœ… **Offline analysis**: Work with events without network access
- âœ… **Structured storage**: Follows well-known conventions
- âœ… **No overwrites**: Preserves existing data safely
- âœ… **Flexible usage**: Works with all existing CLI modes

## File Structure Example
```
./
â”œâ”€â”€ .well-known/
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ did/
â”‚       â””â”€â”€ nostr/
â”‚           â””â”€â”€ event/
â”‚               â”œâ”€â”€ abc123def456...json
â”‚               â”œâ”€â”€ def456ghi789...json
â”‚               â””â”€â”€ ghi789jkl012...json
â”œâ”€â”€ events.json  (if using > redirect)
â””â”€â”€ ...
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] `--save` flag added to CLI argument parsing
- [ ] Directory structure created automatically
- [ ] Events saved as individual JSON files
- [ ] No overwriting of existing files
- [ ] Works with all existing CLI modes (default, interactive, etc.)
- [ ] Profile data included when available
- [ ] Error handling for filesystem issues
- [ ] Updated help text and documentation

issue.title: [android] update AOT profile for .NET 10 RC 1
issue.body:
I tested this with a "franken-build", using `System.Private.CoreLib.dll` from this PR:

* https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/118761

With the `Type.GetType()` revert in place for Mono, I'm getting good startup on an Android Pixel 5 (old) device with the `dotnet new maui` project template:

Comparing the updated AOT profile:

    Before:
    Average(ms): 624.9
    Std Err(ms): 3.77844765302719
    Std Dev(ms): 11.9485006032835
    After:
    Average(ms): 582.1
    Std Err(ms): 2.92289810519172
    Std Dev(ms): 9.24301538099625

Some of my past numbers were on a Pixel 7, so these are good numbers for an even older device.

We may want to run this again with newer (less-franken!) builds, but this is worth merging for now.
